    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Use <a href=\"http://junit.sourceforge.net/javadoc/org/junit/Assert.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">org.junit.Assert</a>'s method <code>assertArrayEquals</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import org.junit.Assert;\n...\n\nAssert.assertArrayEquals( expectedResult, result );\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If this method is not available, you may have accidentally imported the Assert class from <code>junit.framework</code>. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 345995,
      "reputation" : 7303,
      "user_id" : 679240,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 61,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c6c18851c01fa33057f636caea371047?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Haroldo_OK",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/679240/haroldo-ok"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1453888983,
    "creation_date" : 1453888983,
    "answer_id" : 35034192,
    "question_id" : 4228161,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I know the question is for JUnit4, but if you happen to be stuck at JUnit3, you could create a short utility function like that:</p>\n\n<pre><code>private void assertArrayEquals(Object[] esperado, Object[] real) {\n    assertEquals(Arrays.asList(esperado), Arrays.asList(real));     \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>In JUnit3, this is better than directly comparing the arrays, since it will detail exactly which elements are different.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
