    "creation_date" : 1455354931,
    "answer_id" : 35378116,
    "question_id" : 4228161,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I prefer to convert arrays to strings:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Assert.assertEquals(\n                Arrays.toString(values),\n                Arrays.toString(new int[] { 7, 8, 9, 3 }));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>this way I can see clearly where wrong values are. This works effectively only for small sized arrays, but I rarely use arrays with more items than 7 in my unit tests.</p>\n\n<p>This method works for primitive types and for other types when overload of <code>toString</code> returns all essential information.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4097974,
      "reputation" : 61,
      "user_id" : 3364242,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/738ed79776b65078d1191e678d1edce5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "winstanr",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3364242/winstanr"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1504592251,
    "last_edit_date" : 1504592251,
    "creation_date" : 1504591156,
    "answer_id" : 46047888,
    "question_id" : 4228161,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Using junit4 and <a href=\"http://hamcrest.org/JavaHamcrest/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Hamcrest</a> you get a concise method of comparing arrays. It also  gives details of where the error is in the failure trace.</p>\n\n<pre><code>import static org.junit.Assert.*\nimport static org.hamcrest.CoreMatchers.*;\n\n//...\n\nassertThat(result, is(new int[] {56, 100, 2000}));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Failure Trace output:</p>\n\n<pre><code>java.lang.AssertionError: \n   Expected: is [&lt;56&gt;, &lt;100&gt;, &lt;2000&gt;]\n   but: was [&lt;55&gt;, &lt;100&gt;, &lt;2000&gt;]\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 230460,
      "reputation" : 24956,
      "user_id" : 494074,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 76,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/741e480d426fabd85825861bd6481ccd?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ankur Agarwal",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/494074/ankur-agarwal"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1756161658,
    "last_edit_date" : 1756161658,
    "creation_date" : 1608529261,
    "answer_id" : 65387994,
    "question_id" : 4228161,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>See <a href=\"https://docs.junit.org/current/api/org.junit.jupiter.api/org/junit/jupiter/api/Assertions.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Assertions</code></a> class in Jupiter Javadoc.</p>\n<p>Use:</p>\n<pre><code>public static void assertArrayEquals(int[] expected,\n                                     int[] actual)\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
